Let T be a left exact functor from \mathscr {A} to an abelian category \mathscr {B}.
    Suppose that every object of \mathscr {A} injects into an injective object.
    The functor T can then be "derived" to give the functors

    1074hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.1hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.1.xmlEquation7.1.3.1         \mathrm {R}\colon          \mathrm {D}^+(\mathscr {A})         \to  \mathrm {D}^+(\mathscr {B})       \tag{7.1.3.1}       

    1075hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.2hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.2.xmlEquation7.1.3.2         \mathrm {R}\colon          \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(\mathscr {A})         \to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(\mathscr {B})       \tag{7.1.3.2}       

    1076hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.3hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.3.xmlEquation7.1.3.3         \mathrm {R}\colon          \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(\mathscr {A})         \to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(\mathscr {B}).       \tag{7.1.3.3}       

    They can be calculated as follows: if K' is a T-acyclic resolution (resp. a filtered resolution, resp. a bifiltered resolution) of K ( and ), then \mathrm {R} T(K)=T(K').

Let T be a left exact functor from \mathscr {A} to an abelian category \mathscr {B}.
    Suppose that every object of \mathscr {A} injects into an injective object.
    The functor T can then be "derived" to give the functors

    1074hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.1hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.1.xmlEquation7.1.3.1         \mathrm {R}\colon          \mathrm {D}^+(\mathscr {A})         \to  \mathrm {D}^+(\mathscr {B})       \tag{7.1.3.1}       

    1075hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.2hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.2.xmlEquation7.1.3.2         \mathrm {R}\colon          \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(\mathscr {A})         \to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(\mathscr {B})       \tag{7.1.3.2}       

    1076hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.3hodge-theory-iii-7.1.3.3.xmlEquation7.1.3.3         \mathrm {R}\colon          \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(\mathscr {A})         \to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(\mathscr {B}).       \tag{7.1.3.3}       

    They can be calculated as follows: if K' is a T-acyclic resolution (resp. a filtered resolution, resp. a bifiltered resolution) of K ( and ), then \mathrm {R} T(K)=T(K').

If K is filtered (resp. bifiltered), then \mathrm {R}{a_\bullet }_*K is filtered (resp. bifiltered): we have

    2641hodge-theory-iii-7.1.5.1hodge-theory-iii-7.1.5.1.xmlEquation7.1.5.1         \mathrm {R}{a_\bullet }_*         \colon  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(X_\bullet )         \to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(S_\bullet )       \tag{7.1.5.1}       

    2642hodge-theory-iii-7.1.5.2hodge-theory-iii-7.1.5.2.xmlEquation7.1.5.2         \mathrm {R}{a_\bullet }_*         \colon  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(X_\bullet )         \to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(S_\bullet ).       \tag{7.1.5.2}

Let K be a complex of cosimplicial sheaves on S, endowed with an increasing filtration W.
    We define the diagonal filtration \delta (W,L) of W and L to be the increasing filtration of \mathrm {s} K given by

    2644hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.1hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.1.xmlEquation7.1.6.1         \begin {aligned}           \delta (W,L)_n(\mathrm {s} K)           &= \bigoplus _{p,q} W_{n+p}(K^{p,q})         \\&= \sum _p \mathrm {s}(W_{n+p}(K)) \cap  L^p(\mathrm {s} K).         \end {aligned}       \tag{7.1.6.1}

The functor (K,W)\mapsto (\mathrm {s} K,\delta (W,L)) sends filtered quasi-isomorphisms to filtered quasi-isomorphisms, and defines

    2646hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.3hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.3.xmlEquation7.1.6.3         \begin {aligned}           (s,\delta )           \colon  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(S_\bullet )           &\to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(S)         \\(K,W)           &\mapsto  (\mathrm {s} K,\delta (W,L))         \end {aligned}       \tag{7.1.6.3}       

    whence, by composition with ,

    2647hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.4hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.4.xmlEquation7.1.6.4         \begin {aligned}           (\mathrm {R}\Gamma ,\delta (-,L))           \colon  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(X_\bullet )           &\to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(S)         \\(K,W)           &\mapsto  (\mathrm {R}\Gamma  K,\delta (W,L)).         \end {aligned}       \tag{7.1.6.4}       

    From , we see that

    2648hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.5hodge-theory-iii-7.1.6.5.xmlEquation7.1.6.5         \operatorname {Gr}_n^{\delta (W,L)}         = \bigoplus _p \mathrm {R}{a_p}_*(\operatorname {Gr}_{n+p}^W K)[-p].       \tag{7.1.6.5}

For example, for increasing W, the functor (K,W,F)\mapsto (K,\delta (W,L),F) sends bifiltered quasi-isomorphisms to bifiltered quasi-isomorphisms, and thus defines

    2650hodge-theory-iii-7.1.7.1hodge-theory-iii-7.1.7.1.xmlEquation7.1.7.1         \begin {aligned}           \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(S_\bullet )           &\to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(S)         \\(K,W,F)           &\mapsto  (K,\delta (W,L),F).         \end {aligned}       \tag{7.1.7.1}       

    By composition with , we thus obtain

    2651hodge-theory-iii-7.1.7.2hodge-theory-iii-7.1.7.2.xmlEquation7.1.7.2         \begin {aligned}           \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(X_\bullet )           &\to  \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}_2(S)         \\(K,W,F)           &\mapsto  (\mathrm {R}\Gamma  K,\delta (W,L),F).         \end {aligned}       \tag{7.1.7.2}       

    and we have that

    2652hodge-theory-iii-7.1.7.3hodge-theory-iii-7.1.7.3.xmlEquation7.1.7.3         \operatorname {Gr}_n^{\delta (W,L)}(\mathrm {R}\Gamma  K,F)         = \bigoplus _p \mathrm {R}{a_p}_*(\operatorname {Gr}_{n+p}^W K,F)[-p]       \tag{7.1.7.3}       

    in \mathrm {D}^+\mathrm {F}(S).

If K' is a bifiltered T-acyclic resolution of K, then the complex TK' is filtered by the TF^pK' and the TW^qK' ().
    Furthermore, \operatorname {Gr}_W^n(K') is a T-acyclic filtered (for F) resolution of \operatorname {Gr}_F^n(K), and \operatorname {Gr}_F^n\operatorname {Gr}_W^m(K') is a T-acyclic resolution of \operatorname {Gr}_F^n\operatorname {Gr}_W^m(K), and
           \begin {gathered}         T\operatorname {Gr}_F K'         \approx  \operatorname {Gr}_F TK'         \qquad \text {as }W\text {-filtered complexes}       \\T\operatorname {Gr}_W K'         \approx  \operatorname {Gr}_W TK'         \qquad \text {as }F\text {-filtered complexes}       \\T\operatorname {Gr}_F\operatorname {Gr}_W K'         \approx  \operatorname {Gr}_F\operatorname {Gr}_W TK'.       \end {gathered}
